values
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:misc:f004ca54', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> \"To explain how unemployment affected the budget, I''ll describe how the government used fiscal policy to cut unemployment.\"</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> This is a Misconception the examiners named directly on this paper: a reasonable number of candidates misunderstood the question and wrote about how the government ACHIEVED lower unemployment through expansionary fiscal policy. That was not what the question asked. The question runs the other way — unemployment CHANGED, and you must trace what that change DID to the budget (more workers → more income tax/NI/VAT; fewer claimants → less benefit spending → smaller deficit). Check the direction of causation before you start writing: is the policy the cause, or the consequence?</p>", "question": "''Analyse how changes in unemployment affected the government''s budget'' asks you to...", "options": ["Trace what the unemployment change did to tax revenue and spending", "Explain how fiscal policy reduced unemployment", "Describe the unemployment rate", "Evaluate whether the policy worked"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Unemployment is the CAUSE and the budget is the effect. Writing about fiscal policy reducing unemployment reverses the causation and scores nothing."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:misc:696f5f5a', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> \"Someone earning £20,000 pays 20% income tax, so £4,000. And someone on £45,000 pays 20%.\"</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Two errors in one. First, the examiners reported that a significant proportion of candidates did NOT factor in the £11,850 Personal Allowance: tax = 20% × (£20,000 − £11,850) = **£1,630**, not £4,000. (Some who did remember it then wrongly used £11,851.) Second, don''t confuse the MARGINAL rate with the AVERAGE rate actually paid. On £45,000 with a £12,500 allowance, tax = 20% × £32,500 = £6,500 — which is only **14%** of the full £45,000, not 20%. Bands are marginal, so the average rate is always lower than the top rate you touch. And the £ sign is required for full marks.</p>", "question": "With a £12,500 allowance and 20% basic rate, someone earning £45,000 pays what % of their income in tax?", "options": ["20%", "0%", "About 14%", "29%"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "20% × (£45,000 − £12,500) = £6,500, which is 14% of £45,000. The 20% is the marginal rate — the average rate paid is always lower."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:misc:61b74f5d', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> \"A positive externality of NHS spending is that patients get better healthcare.\"</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> The examiners flagged this: a significant proportion identified DIRECT impacts such as ''better health care'' — but that is the benefit to the person treated, not an externality. An externality is a spillover to THIRD PARTIES who were not part of the transaction. Credited answers name who else gains and how: vaccinations stop contagious diseases spreading, so even the unvaccinated are safer; education lowers crime, so the whole community benefits; parks improve air quality for everyone nearby. This matters beyond the 2-marker — it is exactly why the extract says health ''provision through markets would not be ideal'': left to the market, goods with positive externalities are UNDER-provided, which is the market limitation government spending corrects.</p>", "question": "Which is a genuine positive externality of government spending?", "options": ["Pupils at school gain qualifications", "Patients treated by the NHS get better healthcare", "Vaccinations stop diseases spreading to people who weren''t vaccinated", "Benefit claimants receive more money"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "An externality benefits THIRD parties. The others are direct benefits to the people receiving the service — the exact error the examiners flagged."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:misc:4bbbe207', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> \"Cutting income tax raises disposable income, so demand rises and growth follows. Done.\"</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> That is the textbook effect, and stopping there is what the examiners called an unsubstantiated answer. Real behaviour can defeat it — this is where the evaluation marks are. People may SAVE the tax cut rather than spend it, especially if worried about the economy; or spend it on IMPORTS, which helps foreign producers and worsens the balance of payments (a real MCQ: expansionary fiscal policy risks a balance of payments deficit). A tax cut meant to make people work MORE may lead them to work LESS for the same money. And raising spending only raises output if supply can respond — near full employment you get demand-pull inflation instead. The extract itself warns of exactly this. Always name what it DEPENDS on: spare capacity, and whether households spend or save.</p>", "question": "Why might cutting income tax fail to raise demand for domestic output?", "options": ["Taxes never affect income", "Households may save it, or spend it on imports", "It automatically causes unemployment", "Firms are forced to raise prices"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "Two unintended effects: saving instead of spending (especially if confidence is low), or buying imports — which benefits foreign producers and worsens the current account."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:tips:eeff3e53', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "definition — Definitions: name both halves, and use the right label", "reading": "<p>These are free marks if you have the exact wording:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Direct vs indirect tax</strong> = 1 mark for a characteristic of either; <strong>2 marks only for the DIFFERENCE</strong> — the liable person pays a direct tax; an indirect tax is paid over by someone else.</li>\n<li><strong>Two measures of fiscal policy</strong>: government expenditure, taxes, budget deficit/borrowing/surplus. (Only ONE instance of tax or spending counts.)</li>\n<li><strong>Two areas of government spending</strong>: social protection, health, education, defence.</li>\n<li><strong>Two direct taxes other than income tax</strong>: inheritance, corporation, capital gains, National Insurance, council tax. The examiners noted \"some evidence of confusion between direct and indirect taxes\".</li>\n<li><strong>Why the public sector borrowed £35.9bn</strong>: \"government spending is higher than tax revenue\" earns BOTH marks on its own.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "For ''explain the difference between direct and indirect taxation'', what earns 2 marks rather than 1?", "options": ["Naming one example of each", "Saying which raises more revenue", "Identifying the DIFFERENCE — who actually pays it over", "Defining tax"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "The mark scheme gives 1 mark for a characteristic of either, but 2 marks only for correctly identifying the difference between them."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:tips:1bc03d3f', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "calculation — Calculations: allowances first, then the right denominator", "reading": "<p>Four calculation types recur, each with its own trap:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Income tax</strong>: subtract the Personal Allowance FIRST. 20% × (£20,000 − £11,850) = <strong>£1,630</strong>. The £ sign is required.</li>\n<li><strong>Average tax rate</strong>: divide by TOTAL income, not the taxed slice. £6,500 ÷ £45,000 = <strong>14%</strong>, not 20%.</li>\n<li><strong>An average over years</strong>: use the TOTAL row only. (384.0 + 675.5 + 952.3) ÷ 3 = <strong>£670.6bn</strong>.</li>\n<li><strong>VAT on a bill</strong>: apply each rate to its own item then add BOTH totals — £400 × 1.20 + £50 × 1.08 = <strong>£534</strong> (the total spend, not the tax).</li>\n<li><strong>Biggest increase ≠ biggest number</strong>: subtract consecutive years. 2016–17 rose £35.6bn even though 2017–18 has the highest total.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "Total government spending was 384.0, 675.5 and 952.3 (£bn). The average per year is...", "options": ["£2011.8bn", "£952.3bn", "£568.2bn", "£670.6bn"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "(384.0 + 675.5 + 952.3) ÷ 3 = £670.6bn. Use the TOTAL row, not the individual spending lines."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:tips:40a901ea', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "diagrams — The indirect tax diagram: shift S left, then chain it", "reading": "<p>The petrol/CO2 question needs a diagram AND the reasoning linked to it:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Draw it properly</strong>: an initial equilibrium; supply shifted <strong>LEFT</strong>; the second curve labelled <strong>\"S + tax\"</strong> (or S1); <strong>quantity of petrol</strong> on the horizontal axis; the vertical gap between curves = the tax per unit.</li>\n<li><strong>Then the chain</strong>: the tax increases the cost of production → supply decreases → equilibrium price of petrol rises → equilibrium quantity falls → less petrol burned → <strong>lower CO2 emissions</strong>.</li>\n<li><strong>Add the PED point</strong>: the extract says when demand is price inelastic, the change in quantity is LESS. Petrol has few substitutes, so emissions fall only modestly.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "On the petrol indirect-tax diagram, the second supply curve should be labelled...", "options": ["S − tax, shifted right", "S + tax (or S1), shifted to the LEFT", "It needs no label", "D + tax, shifted right"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "The mark scheme awards application marks specifically for labelling the second S as ''S + tax'' or ''S1/S2'', shifted left, with quantity of petrol on the horizontal axis."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:tips:6cf64db8', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "evaluate — Evaluate: cover BOTH sides, then say what it depends on", "reading": "<p>The examiners were explicit: <strong>\"the question asked that costs AND benefits are discussed, so reference to both is required to achieve Level 3.\"</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Don''t list.</strong> \"Candidates should not produce a list of good/bad points or unconnected advantages/disadvantages. A good evaluative point should strengthen, mitigate or contrast with a key point.\"</li>\n<li><strong>Watch for \"purely\".</strong> \"Would raising tax on the richest 20% be PURELY beneficial?\" is an invitation to show it is not — revenue rises, but so do disincentives, avoidance and migration.</li>\n<li><strong>Use the inelasticity pivot</strong> on tobacco: inelastic demand makes the tax great for revenue (£9.5bn) but weak at cutting smoking — and regressive, since £6.82 on a £9.16 packet takes a bigger share of a poor smoker''s income.</li>\n<li><strong>Support the judgement.</strong> The examiners criticised \"an unsubstantiated judgement at the end\". Name the condition: spare capacity, or whether households spend rather than save.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "For ''evaluate whether the benefits of fiscal policy are greater than the costs'', what is required for Level 3?", "options": ["As many benefits as possible", "Quoting the extract in full", "Both costs AND benefits, plus a supported judgement", "A long list of advantages and disadvantages"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "The mark scheme states both must be covered for Level 3, and the examiners criticised unconnected lists and unsubstantiated judgements."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:fib:10cf75d8', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'fib', 'fib', 2, '{"question": "Fiscal policy is the government''s choices about ___B1___ and ___B2___.", "blankOptions": {"B1": ["left", "taxation", "multiplier", "deficit"], "B2": ["cutting", "left", "spending", "borrowed"]}}'::jsonb, '{"blanks": {"B1": "taxation", "B2": "spending"}}'::jsonb),
