('economics:3-5-fiscal-policy:match:b9aa5dc6', 'economics', 'economics:3-5-fiscal-policy', '3.5 Fiscal Policy', 'match', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which definition matches the key term “Unintended effects”?", "options": ["A tax on spending, collected and passed on by the seller", "Money given to encourage goods with positive externalities", "The government''s choices about taxation and spending", "Outcomes a policy causes that the government did not intend"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "“Unintended effects” means: Outcomes a policy causes that the government did not intend"}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-6-monetary-policy:exam:1e628af3', 'economics', 'economics:3-6-monetary-policy', '3.6 Monetary Policy', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q2", "question": "How may quantitative easing affect the economy?", "options": ["The money supply will decrease", "The rate of inflation will decrease", "Unemployment will decrease", "Wealth inequality will decrease"], "caseStudy": "<p>The Bank of England has used a policy of quantitative easing as part of monetary policy since 2009.</p>", "hint": "QE increases the money supply and lowers interest rates, boosting total demand — what does more demand typically do to unemployment and to inflation?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1b)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: C — Unemployment will decrease</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>QE increases the money supply and should reduce interest rates, increasing total demand, which is likely to reduce unemployment. Option A is the opposite of QE, and inflation is likely to increase (rendering B incorrect).</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-6-monetary-policy:exam:bf91f637', 'economics', 'economics:3-6-monetary-policy', '3.6 Monetary Policy', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q4", "question": "Interest rates fall. Which of the following is most likely to fall as a result?", "options": ["Firms'' investment", "Household savings", "Overall employment", "Gross domestic product"], "hint": "A rate cut makes saving LESS rewarding. Investment, employment and GDP would all be expected to RISE as demand increases — only one of these four falls.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1b)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: B — Household savings</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>A cut makes saving less attractive, so households save less. Investment, employment and GDP should all rise as demand increases.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5>\n<p>A very high percentage of candidates gave Option B as the correct response to this question.</p>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-6-monetary-policy:exam:92073ce6', 'economics', 'economics:3-6-monetary-policy', '3.6 Monetary Policy', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q6", "question": "The Bank of England has decided to raise interest rates in order to reduce inflation. As a result", "options": ["borrowing by firms rises", "external value of the UK pound (£) falls", "government revenue falls", "saving by households rises"], "hint": "Higher rates make saving more rewarding, so households save more, not less. Borrowing would fall (not rise), and a rate rise tends to STRENGTHEN the pound, not weaken it.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1b)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: D — saving by households rises</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Higher rates make saving more rewarding, so household saving rises. Borrowing by firms would fall, the pound would tend to strengthen (not fall), and government revenue is not the direct effect being tested here.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-6-monetary-policy:exam:fa5a41ab', 'economics', 'economics:3-6-monetary-policy', '3.6 Monetary Policy', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q7", "question": "Monetary policy aims to:", "options": ["control the total supply of money in the economy", "create new money in order to control the economy", "increase the supply of money available to consumers", "increase the use of money as a medium of exchange"], "hint": "Monetary policy is the manipulation of interest rates, the money supply and exchange rates — this option describes controlling the total money supply, the core definition. The others only describe one narrow (and sometimes wrong) slice of it.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1a)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: A — control the total supply of money in the economy</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>This is the core definition of monetary policy. Creating new money (B) is only one possible tool (QE), not the overall aim; C and D describe only narrow or inaccurate slices of it.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-6-monetary-policy:exam:190e6253', 'economics', 'economics:3-6-monetary-policy', '3.6 Monetary Policy', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q8", "question": "Which of the following is a consequence of inflation for consumers?", "options": ["Fall in tax revenue", "Increase in menu costs", "Real incomes may fall", "Savings increase in value"], "hint": "Menu costs fall on producers, tax revenue is a government concern, and inflation REDUCES the real value of savings — only one option correctly names an effect on CONSUMERS.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1a)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: C — Real incomes may fall</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>If prices rise faster than wages, consumers'' real incomes fall. Menu costs fall on producers, tax revenue is a government issue, and inflation REDUCES the real value of savings.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-6-monetary-policy:exam:6797cc12', 'economics', 'economics:3-6-monetary-policy', '3.6 Monetary Policy', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q9", "question": "Under which of the following circumstances would it be best to be a lender?", "options": ["The nominal rate of interest is 0 percent and the inflation rate is 0 percent", "The nominal rate of interest is 2 percent and the inflation rate is 5 percent", "The nominal rate of interest is 5 percent and the inflation rate is 1 percent", "The nominal rate of interest is 7 percent and the inflation rate is 4 percent"], "hint": "A lender wants the highest REAL return (nominal − inflation). Work out each: 0%, −3%, +4%, +3%. The highest nominal rate is not always the best deal.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO2) · Quantitative skills</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: C — nominal 5%, inflation 1%</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Real rate = nominal − inflation. A: 0 − 0 = 0%. B: 2 − 5 = −3%. C: 5 − 1 = <strong>+4%</strong>. D: 7 − 4 = +3%. C gives the highest real return, even though D has the higher nominal rate — the trap.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-6-monetary-policy:exam:eedc6719', 'economics', 'economics:3-6-monetary-policy', '3.6 Monetary Policy', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q10", "question": "Monetary policy is most likely to affect", "options": ["real output and indirect taxes", "the price level and indirect taxes", "the price level and real output", "the price level but not real output"], "hint": "Interest rate changes shift total demand, which affects BOTH how much is produced (real output) AND the general level of prices — not taxes, which are a fiscal policy tool.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO2)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: C — the price level and real output</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Changing interest rates shifts total demand, which affects both output and prices. Indirect taxes are a fiscal policy tool, not a monetary one.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-6-monetary-policy:exam:4aa58cc7', 'economics', 'economics:3-6-monetary-policy', '3.6 Monetary Policy', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q11", "question": "The central bank decides to increase quantitative easing. The most likely effect on investment is that it would", "options": ["decrease", "fall at first and then increase", "increase", "remain constant"], "hint": "QE raises the money supply and tends to keep interest rates low, making borrowing to invest cheaper — what does that do to investment?", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO2)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: C — increase</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>More QE raises the money supply and keeps borrowing cheap, encouraging firms to invest more.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-6-monetary-policy:exam:39e0d339', 'economics', 'economics:3-6-monetary-policy', '3.6 Monetary Policy', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q12", "question": "Which pair of events is most likely to happen as a result of a rise in the rate of interest?", "options": ["Asset prices fall and savings by households rise", "Borrowing by firms rises and savings by households fall", "Consumer prices rise and asset prices fall", "External value of the currency falls and borrowing rises"], "hint": "A rate rise makes saving more rewarding (assets like housing become relatively less attractive, so asset prices can fall) — check each pair against that single idea, only one pair is fully consistent.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO2)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: A — Asset prices fall and savings by households rise</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Both effects follow from saving becoming more rewarding relative to holding assets like housing. The other pairs each contain one effect that moves in the wrong direction.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-6-monetary-policy:exam:895550ad', 'economics', 'economics:3-6-monetary-policy', '3.6 Monetary Policy', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q14", "question": "Monetary policy can have an effect on:", "options": ["both the price level and the level of output", "neither the price level or the level of output", "the level of output but not on the price level", "the price level but not on the level of output"], "hint": "A change in interest rates shifts total demand, which moves BOTH prices and output — not just one of them.", "starter": "The correct answer is..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\">\n<h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1b)</h5>\n<p><strong>Answer: A — both the price level and the level of output</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Interest rate changes shift total demand, affecting both real output and the general price level.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-6-monetary-policy:mcq:f54be61e', 'economics', 'economics:3-6-monetary-policy', '3.6 Monetary Policy', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Who is responsible for setting the UK''s base rate of interest?", "options": ["The Prime Minister", "The Chancellor of the Exchequer", "The high street banks", "The Bank of England''s Monetary Policy Committee"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "The MPC sets the base rate independently of government — a common misconception is that the government sets rates directly."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-6-monetary-policy:mcq:8119ef16', 'economics', 'economics:3-6-monetary-policy', '3.6 Monetary Policy', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "The UK government''s inflation target is...", "options": ["2%, with a margin of 1% either way", "5%, to encourage spending", "10%, to match average wage growth", "0%, i.e. no inflation at all"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "The target is 2%, and the Bank is content with inflation anywhere between 1% and 3% either side of it."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-6-monetary-policy:mcq:e55f5851', 'economics', 'economics:3-6-monetary-policy', '3.6 Monetary Policy', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "If the Bank of England raises the base rate, what is the most likely direct effect on firms'' investment?", "options": ["It rises, because banks lend more when rates are high", "It rises, because firms earn higher returns on investment", "It falls, because borrowing to invest becomes more expensive", "It stays the same, because investment doesn''t depend on interest rates"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "Higher rates raise the cost of borrowing, so fewer investment projects remain profitable. A common exam mistake is to say investment rises because of ''higher returns'' — that confuses investing with saving."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-6-monetary-policy:mcq:f473f02a', 'economics', 'economics:3-6-monetary-policy', '3.6 Monetary Policy', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Higher UK interest rates (relative to other countries) tend to cause the pound to...", "options": ["Stay the same, because interest rates don''t affect exchange rates", "Depreciate, because exports become cheaper", "Depreciate, as UK residents buy more imports", "Appreciate, as foreign investors buy pounds for the better return"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "Higher UK rates attract foreign savers/investors, raising demand for pounds (or reducing their supply), so the pound appreciates."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-6-monetary-policy:mcq:c0da8f33', 'economics', 'economics:3-6-monetary-policy', '3.6 Monetary Policy', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which of these is a tool of monetary policy, not fiscal policy?", "options": ["Increasing government spending on the NHS", "Quantitative easing", "Raising income tax", "Cutting VAT"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "Monetary policy (interest rates, money supply, exchange rates) is controlled by the Bank of England. Fiscal policy (tax and spending) is controlled by the government."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-6-monetary-policy:mcq:d613c1db', 'economics', 'economics:3-6-monetary-policy', '3.6 Monetary Policy', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Quantitative easing is most likely to be used when...", "options": ["The government wants to raise more tax revenue", "Interest rates are already very low and cutting them further would have little effect", "Inflation is far above target and needs to fall quickly", "Interest rates are very high and need to come down gradually"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "QE creates money to buy assets and raise the money supply, used when rates are already near zero and can''t usefully be cut further — as in 2009 and during the pandemic."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-6-monetary-policy:mcq:1192bce0', 'economics', 'economics:3-6-monetary-policy', '3.6 Monetary Policy', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "A cut in the base rate is most likely to lead to...", "options": ["Lower consumer spending and higher unemployment", "Higher saving and lower borrowing", "Higher consumer spending and lower unemployment", "No change in demand, only in prices"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "Cheaper borrowing and less reward for saving raise total demand, so firms raise output and take on more workers — higher spending, lower unemployment."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-6-monetary-policy:mcq:fa838353', 'economics', 'economics:3-6-monetary-policy', '3.6 Monetary Policy', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which group is most directly and consistently affected by changes in the interest rate paid on savings?", "options": ["Students with no savings", "Firms with no bank loans", "Pensioners who rely on savings income", "Tourists visiting the UK"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "Pensioners often depend on income from savings to live, so they are directly and consistently exposed to changes in the savings rate, unlike the other groups listed."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-6-monetary-policy:mcq:73da3784', 'economics', 'economics:3-6-monetary-policy', '3.6 Monetary Policy', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "For a 6-mark ''Analyse'' question on monetary policy, which skill is NOT required or rewarded?", "options": ["A developed chain of reasoning", "Correct use of economic terminology", "Reference to the extract or context", "A weighed, supported evaluative judgement"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "Examiners have explicitly said evaluative comments are ''not a skill required (nor rewardable)'' on an Analyse question — save judgement for questions marked with an asterisk that say ''Evaluate''."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-6-monetary-policy:mcq:d32c5777', 'economics', 'economics:3-6-monetary-policy', '3.6 Monetary Policy', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "The single biggest factor in whether a change in interest rates has the effect economic theory predicts is often...", "options": ["The number of MPC members who voted for the change", "The total value of UK exports", "The rate of UK population growth", "Consumer and business confidence"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "Low confidence can stop the textbook chain from playing out — for example, people may keep saving despite a rate cut, or firms may not invest even when borrowing is cheap."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-6-monetary-policy:tf:ce155384', 'economics', 'economics:3-6-monetary-policy', '3.6 Monetary Policy', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "The UK government directly sets the Bank of England''s base rate."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "The base rate is set by the Bank of England''s Monetary Policy Committee (MPC), which is independent of government — a deliberate design to stop rates being manipulated for short-term political reasons."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-6-monetary-policy:tf:05c23fc6', 'economics', 'economics:3-6-monetary-policy', '3.6 Monetary Policy', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Raising interest rates is intended to reduce demand-pull inflation."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "Higher rates make borrowing dearer and saving more rewarding, reducing total demand — which directly eases demand-pull inflationary pressure."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-6-monetary-policy:tf:c4b9ddbc', 'economics', 'economics:3-6-monetary-policy', '3.6 Monetary Policy', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "A cut in interest rates tends to increase unemployment."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "A rate cut raises demand, so firms raise output and take on more workers — lowering, not raising, unemployment."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-6-monetary-policy:tf:1be3ac6a', 'economics', 'economics:3-6-monetary-policy', '3.6 Monetary Policy', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Quantitative easing involves the Bank of England creating money to buy financial assets."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "QE is the Bank creating money electronically to buy assets, mainly government bonds, raising the money supply and encouraging lending and spending."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-6-monetary-policy:tf:0099660e', 'economics', 'economics:3-6-monetary-policy', '3.6 Monetary Policy', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Higher UK interest rates (relative to other countries) tend to make the pound depreciate."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "Higher rates attract foreign savers seeking the better return, raising demand for the pound — so it tends to APPRECIATE, not depreciate."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-6-monetary-policy:tf:06737166', 'economics', 'economics:3-6-monetary-policy', '3.6 Monetary Policy', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Monetary policy and fiscal policy use exactly the same tools."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "Monetary policy uses interest rates, the money supply and exchange rates, controlled by the Bank of England. Fiscal policy uses tax and government spending, controlled by the government — different tools, different bodies."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-6-monetary-policy:tf:544e9a99', 'economics', 'economics:3-6-monetary-policy', '3.6 Monetary Policy', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "On a 6-mark ''Analyse'' question, adding evaluative comments earns extra credit."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "Examiners have explicitly said evaluation ''is not a skill required (nor rewardable)'' on an Analyse question — it wastes time without extra marks."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-6-monetary-policy:tf:4ff94076', 'economics', 'economics:3-6-monetary-policy', '3.6 Monetary Policy', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Pensioners are particularly affected by changes in interest rates paid on savings, because they often rely on savings income."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "Unlike many other groups, pensioners frequently depend on savings income to live, so they are directly and consistently exposed to rate changes."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-6-monetary-policy:learn:f54be61e', 'economics', 'economics:3-6-monetary-policy', '3.6 Monetary Policy', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "What is monetary policy? The Bank of England and the base rate", "reading": "<p><strong>Monetary policy is the manipulation of interest rates, the money supply and exchange rates to influence the level of economic activity.</strong> Its primary target is a low, stable rate of inflation.</p>\n<h4>Who actually sets UK interest rates — a very common misconception</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Interest rates are set by the <strong>Bank of England''s Monetary Policy Committee (MPC)</strong> — NOT the government. Writing \"the government sets interest rates\" is a real, frequently-tested error.</li>\n<li>The MPC has <strong>9 members</strong>: the Governor of the Bank of England, three Deputy Governors, the Bank''s Chief Economist, and four external members appointed directly by the Chancellor. It meets regularly to set the <strong>base rate</strong>.</li>\n<li>The UK''s <strong>inflation target is 2%</strong>, with a margin of <strong>1% either way</strong> — the Bank is content with inflation between 1% and 3%.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>How the base rate actually works</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>The base rate is the rate at which the <strong>Bank of England lends to commercial banks</strong>.</li>\n<li>High street banks then set their OWN deposit and loan rates relative to it — paying slightly less on deposits and charging slightly more on loans than the base rate, which is part of how banks make their profit.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Monetary policy vs fiscal policy — do not confuse them</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Monetary policy</strong>: interest rates, the money supply and exchange rates, controlled by the <strong>Bank of England</strong>.</li>\n<li><strong>Fiscal policy</strong>: taxation and government spending, controlled by the <strong>government</strong>.</li>\n<li>Why keep the Bank of England independent? It reduces the risk of interest rates being manipulated for short-term political gain (e.g. cutting rates just before an election) rather than sound long-term economic management — a useful evaluative point.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "Who is responsible for setting the UK''s base rate of interest?", "options": ["The Chancellor of the Exchequer directly", "The Bank of England''s Monetary Policy Committee (MPC)", "The Prime Minister", "Each high street bank sets its own base rate"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "The MPC — 9 members including the Governor and four external members — sets the base rate independently of government. This independence is meant to stop rates being set for short-term political reasons."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-6-monetary-policy:learn:d9bd8f44', 'economics', 'economics:3-6-monetary-policy', '3.6 Monetary Policy', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Raising interest rates — controlling inflation", "reading": "<p>Raising the base rate makes <strong>borrowing more expensive</strong> and <strong>saving more rewarding</strong>. Every effect below flows from those two facts.</p>\n<h4>The chain candidates must be able to write out</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Borrowing:</strong> the cost of borrowing rises, so consumers borrow and spend less (especially on credit and ''big ticket'' items), and firms borrow less to invest — firms also face a higher opportunity cost of investing their own retained profit instead of saving it.</li>\n<li><strong>Saving:</strong> the reward for saving increases, so more is saved and less is spent.</li>\n<li><strong>Mortgage holders:</strong> many UK mortgages are on variable rates, so mortgage payments rise, leaving households with less disposable income to spend.</li>\n<li><strong>Asset prices:</strong> saving becomes more attractive relative to assets like housing, which can push house prices down — homeowners feel poorer (a negative wealth effect), further reducing confidence and spending.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>All of this <strong>reduces total demand</strong>, easing <strong>demand-pull inflation</strong> — but it risks slowing economic growth and raising unemployment. This is the core trade-off examiners test again and again.</p>\n<h4>The exchange rate link — a real MCQ trap</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>If UK interest rates rise above rates overseas, foreign savers and investors move funds into the UK for the better return — <strong>demand for the pound rises</strong> (or, on the alternative accepted route, the <strong>supply of pounds falls</strong> as UK residents stop swapping pounds for foreign currency).</li>\n<li>Either way, the pound <strong>appreciates</strong>. That makes imports cheaper, which eases <strong>cost-push inflation</strong> — but it also makes UK exports more expensive and less competitive abroad, which can worsen the trade balance.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "The Bank of England raises the base rate. What is the most likely DIRECT effect on firms'' investment?", "options": ["It falls, because borrowing to invest becomes more expensive", "It rises, because firms can now earn higher returns", "It is unaffected, since investment doesn''t depend on interest rates", "It rises, because banks are more willing to lend when rates are high"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Higher rates raise the cost of borrowing to invest, so investment falls. Confusing this with firms earning higher RETURNS (which applies to saving money, not investing it) is a real examiner-flagged misconception."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-6-monetary-policy:learn:d613c1db', 'economics', 'economics:3-6-monetary-policy', '3.6 Monetary Policy', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Lowering interest rates, QE, and other objectives", "reading": "<p>Cutting the base rate reverses every channel from the previous topic: cheaper borrowing, less reward for saving, lower mortgage payments, and rising asset prices (a positive wealth effect) all raise demand.</p>\n<h4>The growth and employment chain</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Rising demand means firms raise output to meet it, which requires <strong>more workers</strong> — supporting both <strong>economic growth</strong> and <strong>lower unemployment</strong>. This is why rate cuts are especially used in a recession or a period of low growth.</li>\n<li>The risk, of course, is that rising demand can fuel <strong>demand-pull inflation</strong> — the mirror image of the trade-off from raising rates.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Lower rates and the balance of payments — a genuine two-sided effect</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>Lower UK rates make it less attractive to keep money in UK banks, so funds flow overseas seeking a better return. Less demand for the pound means it <strong>depreciates</strong>.</li>\n<li>A weaker pound makes UK exports cheaper/more competitive and imports dearer, which should <strong>improve the balance of payments</strong>.</li>\n<li><strong>But</strong> dearer imports can also cause inflationary pressure — and if an import is price INELASTIC (e.g. petrol), spending on it can actually RISE even though its price has gone up, worsening the trade position rather than improving it.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Quantitative easing (QE) and quantitative tightening (QT)</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>QE</strong> is used when interest rates are already very low and cutting them further would have little extra effect. The Bank of England creates money electronically and uses it to buy assets — mainly government bonds — from the government and financial institutions, raising the money supply and encouraging lending and spending. Used after the <strong>2009 financial crisis</strong> and at the <strong>start of the pandemic</strong>.</li>\n<li><strong>QT</strong> reverses this: the Bank sells bonds, or does not reinvest funds from maturing bonds, reducing the money supply — tending to raise interest rates and cool inflation.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Objectives beyond price stability</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>\"Other than X, state two macroeconomic objectives\" questions want: <strong>low unemployment</strong>, <strong>economic growth</strong>, a <strong>healthy balance of payments</strong>, a <strong>stable exchange rate</strong>. Do NOT write \"controlling inflation\" if price stability is the objective already excluded — the mark scheme explicitly refuses it.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "Quantitative easing is most likely to be used when...", "options": ["The government wants to raise more tax revenue", "Interest rates are already very low and cutting them further would have little effect", "Inflation is far above target and needs to fall quickly", "Interest rates are very high and need to come down gradually"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "QE is the Bank''s tool for when conventional rate cuts have run out of road — it creates money to buy assets and raise the money supply directly, as it did after the 2009 crisis and at the start of the pandemic."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-6-monetary-policy:learn:703c52d3', 'economics', 'economics:3-6-monetary-policy', '3.6 Monetary Policy', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Evaluating monetary policy — confidence, size, and who''s affected", "reading": "<p>Knowing the CHAIN of effects only gets you to Level 2. Reaching Level 3 on an Evaluate question means questioning HOW MUCH the chain actually plays out.</p>\n<h4>The size of the change matters</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>A sharp rise, like the rapid increases seen in 2022, will have a much bigger effect on saving, borrowing and spending decisions than a change of under 1%, which was typical in earlier years.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Confidence — arguably the single biggest factor</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Consumer confidence:</strong> if it''s low, people may keep saving despite a rate cut (wanting a financial cushion), or stay reluctant to borrow even as rates fall, worried about future repayments. Mortgage holders may not spend extra disposable income from a rate cut if they''re worried about rising prices or future rate rises.</li>\n<li><strong>Business confidence:</strong> low confidence means firms may not invest even at very low rates; high confidence means firms may still invest even at high rates, if they expect strong profits. Banks'' own confidence matters too — after the <strong>2009 credit crunch</strong>, rates were very low, but banks, burned by bad loans, were reluctant to lend to new customers, blunting the policy''s effect.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Not everyone is affected equally</h4>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Savers:</strong> some save toward a fixed goal (a deposit, a car) and may keep saving regardless of the rate; low-income people, who must spend most of what they earn, often can''t save more even when rates rise. <strong>Pensioners</strong> rely on savings income, so they are always directly hit by rate changes.</li>\n<li><strong>Mortgage holders:</strong> roughly <strong>37.5% of the UK population</strong> has a mortgage — worth citing when evaluating how widely a rate change bites. Some can lock in a fixed rate for a period, but are eventually exposed to variable rates.</li>\n<li>A strong evaluation discusses this VARIATION rather than treating \"consumers\" as one uniform group.</li>\n</ul>\n<h4>Analyse vs Evaluate — a skill examiners explicitly separate</h4>\n<ul>\n<li>A 6-mark <strong>Analyse</strong> question does NOT require or reward a judgement — developed chains of reasoning are what score. Adding an evaluative comment wastes time without extra credit.</li>\n<li>A 6-mark <strong>Evaluate</strong> question (marked with an asterisk *) needs a fully supported judgement that weighs both sides.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "Which factor is arguably the single biggest determinant of whether a change in interest rates has the effect economic theory predicts?", "options": ["The total value of UK exports that year", "Consumer and business confidence", "The rate of UK population growth", "How many MPC members voted for the change"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "If confidence is low, expected effects can fail to materialise — people may keep saving despite a rate cut, or firms may not invest even when borrowing is cheap. Confidence shapes whether the textbook chain actually happens."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-6-monetary-policy:misc:c66fb33c', 'economics', 'economics:3-6-monetary-policy', '3.6 Monetary Policy', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> \"If interest rates rise, firms will invest MORE, because they can earn higher returns.\"</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> This is a real, examiner-flagged trap. On the real paper''s Q3(i), ''most candidates identified that investment expenditure would fall because of increased cost/risk. However, a common mistake was that it would increase because of higher returns.'' The confusion is between two DIFFERENT decisions: the reward a firm earns by SAVING spare cash (which does rise with rates) versus the COST of BORROWING to invest in machinery or buildings (which also rises with rates, and is what dominates the investment decision). Higher rates make investment MORE expensive to fund, so investment falls — not rises.</p>", "question": "Interest rates rise. What is the most likely effect on firms'' investment expenditure?", "options": ["It stays exactly the same", "It rises, because banks want to lend more", "It rises, because firms can now earn higher returns on investment", "It falls, because it costs more to borrow to fund investment"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "Examiners specifically flagged ''it would increase because of higher returns'' as a common mistake. The rising COST of borrowing to invest is what matters, and that makes investment fall."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-6-monetary-policy:misc:1849737c', 'economics', 'economics:3-6-monetary-policy', '3.6 Monetary Policy', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> \"When UK interest rates rise, the pound''s value increases because British savers use LESS foreign currency.\"</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Be precise about which market curve actually moves. The mark scheme''s primary route is that DEMAND for pounds rises, because foreign investors move their funds INTO the UK to take advantage of the better return. There is also an accepted alternate route — that SUPPLY of pounds FALLS, because British savers stop exchanging pounds for other currencies. The real paper noted: ''Some candidates confused the increase with saving and less supply of pounds in the foreign exchange market'' — muddling which side of the market is shifting. A small number of sophisticated answers correctly reasoned that falling consumption might reduce imports and therefore reduce supply too, which the examiners praised as ''a sophisticated and logical point.''</p>", "question": "Higher UK interest rates most directly raise the value of the pound because...", "options": ["Government spending on imports falls", "UK exports automatically become cheaper", "The Bank of England prints fewer pounds", "Demand for pounds rises, as foreign investors move funds into the UK for the better return"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "The main accepted route is rising DEMAND for pounds from foreign investors seeking the higher return. A less common but valid alternative is falling SUPPLY of pounds from UK savers who stop exchanging them for other currencies."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-6-monetary-policy:misc:f8788d87', 'economics', 'economics:3-6-monetary-policy', '3.6 Monetary Policy', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> \"An ''Analyse'' 6-mark question should include a supported judgement, just like an ''Evaluate'' question.\"</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> On the real paper''s Q1(a), a 6-mark ''analyse'' question, the examiners wrote: ''Some candidates demonstrated evaluative skills in their answers, which is not a skill required (nor rewardable) for a six-mark analyse question.'' Analyse questions are marked on AO1a (knowledge), AO2 (application) and AO3a (analysis/developed chains of reasoning) — there is no AO3b (evaluation) credit available. Save your weighing-up-both-sides judgement for questions that start with an asterisk (*) and the word ''Evaluate''.</p>", "question": "A 6-mark question asks you to ''Analyse how a cut in interest rates can affect UK economic growth.'' What should your answer focus on?", "options": ["Developed chains of reasoning, with no judgement needed", "A short definition and nothing else", "Describing the extract without adding any economics", "A fully supported judgement weighing costs against benefits"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Analyse questions reward knowledge, application and developed chains of reasoning (AO1a/AO2/AO3a) — not evaluation. Adding a judgement here is wasted effort."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-6-monetary-policy:misc:f4868d1a', 'economics', 'economics:3-6-monetary-policy', '3.6 Monetary Policy', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> \"''Evaluate the impact on UK households'' — I''ll write about the impact on firms instead, since the argument is basically the same.\"</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> On the real paper''s Q3(iii), which asked candidates to evaluate the impact of higher interest rates on UK HOUSEHOLDS, the examiners noted: ''Some candidates did not read the question fully and wrote about effects on firms or generally on the wider economy, rather than households as required.'' Always check exactly which group, or groups, the question names — an otherwise excellent answer about the wrong group scores very little, because the mark scheme rewards points that are clearly linked BACK to the named group.</p>", "question": "A question asks you to ''evaluate the impact of higher interest rates on UK households.'' What is the safest approach?", "options": ["Keep every point explicitly linked back to households, not firms or the whole economy", "Any correct economics about interest rates will score full marks", "Write generally about the whole economy, since households are part of it", "Focus mainly on the effect on firms'' investment"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Examiners specifically penalised candidates who drifted into writing about firms or the wider economy instead of the named group. Read the question and keep every point linked back to it."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-6-monetary-policy:misc:b26c8488', 'economics', 'economics:3-6-monetary-policy', '3.6 Monetary Policy', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> \"Quoting a fact from the extract is enough on its own to get top marks on a 6-mark question.\"</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> On the real paper''s Q5, the examiners wrote: ''Using the context of the extract and question are important components in a question, but theory is needed, on top of direct quotes, to be able to access marks in all the 6 mark questions.'' A quote alone earns little — you must add the ECONOMIC THEORY that explains why the data matters. The same question also flagged a second trap: ''Care was needed regarding the difference between real and nominal.'' Their advice: ''Practise writing about the impact of inflation on the value of saving, debts and purchasing power,'' using words like ''real'', ''nominal'', ''relative'' or ''in comparison'' to be precise.</p>", "question": "For a 6-mark question that gives you a data extract, what do examiners say is needed on top of quoting the data?", "options": ["A conclusion restating the question", "A second, unrelated example", "A longer, more detailed quote", "Economic theory that explains why the data matters"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "The examiners were explicit that context/quotes alone are not enough — candidates need theory as well to access marks on 6-mark questions."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-6-monetary-policy:tips:0f894623', 'economics', 'economics:3-6-monetary-policy', '3.6 Monetary Policy', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "definition — State-and-explain 2-markers: get the direction, then explain it", "reading": "<p>Several 2-mark questions on this paper follow the same pattern, and the mark scheme is unforgiving about the FIRST step:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>State the direction first.</strong> On Q3(i), \"rewardable responses must state that investment will fall/decrease\" — without that, the explanation alone scores nothing.</li>\n<li><strong>Then explain briefly</strong> — one clear reason is enough for the second mark, e.g. \"because it costs more to borrow to invest.\"</li>\n<li><strong>\"Explain what is meant by X\"</strong> questions (e.g. ''the rate of interest'') want a precise definition with TWO elements: the reward for lending/saving AND the cost of borrowing.</li>\n<li><strong>\"Other than X, state two objectives\"</strong> questions explicitly refuse the excluded objective — writing \"controlling inflation\" when price stability is excluded scores nothing.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "On ''state and briefly explain the impact of higher interest rates on firms'' investment'', what is required to access ANY marks?", "options": ["A calculation of the exact fall in investment", "A comparison with another country", "A diagram showing the investment curve", "A clear statement that investment will fall/decrease"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "The mark scheme says rewardable responses MUST state investment will fall/decrease — the explanation only earns the second mark once the direction is correct."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-6-monetary-policy:tips:7e16682f', 'economics', 'economics:3-6-monetary-policy', '3.6 Monetary Policy', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "diagram — Diagram questions: name the curve, name the direction", "reading": "<p>Q13(c) on this paper asks you to analyse, with a diagram, how a fall in interest rates affects the exchange rate — and the mark scheme is blunt: <strong>\"Maximum of 4 marks if no correct diagram.\"</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>The diagram needed is <strong>demand and supply of pounds</strong> against the exchange rate. A fall in interest rates shifts the DEMAND curve for pounds LEFT (D to D1), pulling the exchange rate down from p to p1. A diagram showing supply rising instead is also accepted.</li>\n<li>The vertical axis can show the pound against ANY currency (e.g. $) — that''s fine.</li>\n<li>If you can''t draw on this site, describe it in words: name the curve that moves, the direction it moves, and the resulting change in the equilibrium price — that is exactly what the diagram is checking for.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "On a diagram question about a fall in interest rates and the exchange rate, what happens if you write a correct analysis but include no diagram?", "options": ["You automatically score 0", "You are capped at a maximum of 4 out of 6 marks", "You still qualify for full marks", "The diagram is optional and has no mark impact"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "The mark scheme explicitly caps marks at 4/6 without a correct diagram, even if the written analysis is otherwise strong — the diagram is not optional here."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-6-monetary-policy:tips:f45a93c5', 'economics', 'economics:3-6-monetary-policy', '3.6 Monetary Policy', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "data — Trend questions: find TWO distinct features, not one", "reading": "<p>Q13(b) asks candidates to explain the trend in the UK interest rate chart. The mark scheme rewards TWO separate features, not just \"it went down\":</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Feature 1:</strong> the rate fell sharply, in six stages, over the first 14 months (5.2% → 0.5%).</li>\n<li><strong>Feature 2:</strong> it then stayed low and stable at 0.5% for over seven years (with a brief dip to 0.25%).</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The mark scheme is explicit: <strong>\"explaining these two features should be awarded 2 marks.\"</strong> A single statement like \"the rate fell\" only ever scores 1.</p>", "question": "For ''explain the trends in the UK rate of interest shown in the chart'', what earns full marks?", "options": ["Identifying both the sharp initial fall AND the long stable period that followed", "Stating only that the rate fell overall", "Describing what caused the change", "Naming the exact date of every change"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "The mark scheme rewards two distinct features: the sharp six-stage fall in the first 14 months, and the long stable period at a low rate afterwards."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-6-monetary-policy:tips:b0974c86', 'economics', 'economics:3-6-monetary-policy', '3.6 Monetary Policy', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "evaluate — Analyse & Evaluate: name the group, complete the chain, then judge", "reading": "<p>Every 6-mark question on this paper follows the same AO structure: <strong>AO1a/AO2</strong> for knowledge and application, <strong>AO3a</strong> for analysis, and — on starred (*) questions only — <strong>AO3b</strong> for evaluation.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Complete the chain.</strong> The examiners'' repeated criticism was candidates who \"started a point correctly, however, did not always develop a chain of reasoning fully... missing out the middle section.\"</li>\n<li><strong>Link evaluation points together, don''t just list two unrelated ones.</strong> A common error was writing about a fall in costs for producers \"but not linking to how this may mitigate or offset the fall in demand (& therefore profit).\"</li>\n<li><strong>Name the exact group the question asks about.</strong> \"Evaluate the impact on UK households\" is not the same question as \"on firms\" or \"on the wider economy\" — examiners explicitly penalised drift.</li>\n<li><strong>If a question names TWO groups</strong> (e.g. \"savers and consumers\"), you are capped below Level 3 unless BOTH are addressed — reference to just one is not enough.</li>\n<li><strong>Judge on extent:</strong> the size of the rate change, how long it lasts, and whether confidence is high or low.</li>\n</ul>", "question": "A 6-mark question asks you to analyse how monetary policy protected BOTH savers and consumers. What happens if your answer only covers consumers?", "options": ["You are capped below the top level (Level 3)", "You get full marks as long as consumers are covered well", "You automatically fail the whole question", "It makes no difference to your mark"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "The mark scheme states candidates are capped at a maximum of 5 marks (below Level 3) if both named groups are not addressed — you must link your answer to every group the question names."}'::jsonb),
('economics:3-6-monetary-policy:fib:82be48be', 'economics', 'economics:3-6-monetary-policy', '3.6 Monetary Policy', 'fib', 'fib', 2, '{"question": "Monetary policy is set independently of the ___B1___ by the Bank of England''s ___B2___.", "blankOptions": {"B1": ["unemployment", "government", "depreciate", "fiscal"], "B2": ["depreciate", "MPC", "expensive", "unemployment"]}}'::jsonb, '{"blanks": {"B1": "government", "B2": "MPC"}}'::jsonb),
